Let’s Save Ourselves Some Time

In 2016 the U.S. Forest Service Forest Inventory and Analysis (FIA) project added sapling height to its repertoire of forest research data collected. Tree heights are consistently one of the most time consuming individual pieces of data collected and the requirement has added considerably to total data collection time. The time investment since 2016 has resulted in significant data and the potential for its use to model sapling heights for future inventories should be considered. The plot below shows the data collected in Wisconsin from five species of saplings during 2016, 2017, 2018 and 2019, and the Hours of Effort required to sample height.

“Hours of Effort” is based on an estimate of 25.8 seconds per sapling required to measure height. This estimate was derived by averaging the individual estimates of 21 experienced field employees regarding the number of seconds/sapling required to measure height.

FIA data is public and is available on-line at https://www.fia.fs.fed.us/tools-data/index.php

trees_sum1<-trees%>%
  group_by(SPCD)%>%
  summarize(n=n())
trees_sum1
ggplot()+
  geom_point(data=trees,mapping=aes(x=DIA,y=HT),size=.5,shape=21,fill="forestgreen",color="forestgreen",alpha=.3)+
  facet_grid(.~SPCD)+
  scale_x_continuous(name="Diameter (inches)")+
  scale_y_continuous(name="Total Height (feet)")+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(legend.position="none")+
  geom_smooth(data=trees,mapping=aes(x=DIA,y=HT),method="lm",color="darkgreen",se=FALSE,size=.5)+
  geom_text(data=trees_sum1, mapping=aes(x=3,y=3,label=paste("n=",n),vjust="bottom"))+
  geom_text(data=trees_sum1, mapping=aes(x=3,y=62,label=paste("Hours of Effort=",sprintf("%.01f",(25/60)*n/60))),vjust="bottom",color="firebrick4")+
   labs(title="Sapling Height vs. Diameter for Five Species in WI, 2016-2019",
       subtitle="and the Hours of Effort required for height assessment",
       caption="Total NRS Hours of Effort for 180,559 sapling heights, 2016-2019: 1,281", size=24)

I wanted to look at this data to see how tightly correlated height is to diameter and also to find out how many saplings we are actually sampling. I wanted a little bit of color to create some interest but did NOT want coloring that looked like there should be an associated legend to look for. I wanted the sample size text on the figure to help the viewer understand just how much data we have. I chose five species from WI because it was manageable for this project, was easier to comprehend and provides a pretty good idea of how much data we have and whether height and diameter are tightly correlated enough to use modeled results in the future that would suit our needs. I could pretty this up with colorful titles and strip text etc. but if I’m making a case about how to save time, I don’t want it to look like I spent hours fixing every detail. I still want to get the prediction intervals in here instead of the regression line, but what I see here is a clear correlation between the two variables. This also slightly demonstrates the difference in the relationship for each species which I find interesting. We would likely want to use species, diameter and other variables (such as crown class or physiographic class) to help “tighten” any models produced.

Assessing Total Height of Saplings based on Diameter and Crown Class.

Crown class is assigned to each live sapling/tree measured on FIA plots. Each tree is assigned a code 1-5 signifying where the crown is in relationship to other tree crowns and how much light from above the crown is receiving. I was predicting that factoring in crown class would tighten the correlation between diameter and height. Initially I was interested in using a single species to demonstrate the difference, but then also remembered that I could facet by two variables as I did here. Design choices are based on similar preferences to the plot above. Here I was super excited to sort through how to mutate codes into class names AND to filter out all the NA’s which occur on dead saplings.

ggplot()+
  geom_point(data=trees,mapping=aes(x=DIA,y=HT),size=.5,shape=21,fill="#669933",color="#669933",alpha=.2)+
  facet_grid(SPCD~CCLCD)+
  theme(strip.text=element_text(size=9))+
  scale_x_continuous(name="Diameter (inches)")+
  scale_y_continuous(name="Total Height (feet)")+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(legend.position="none")+
  geom_smooth(data=trees,mapping=aes(x=DIA,y=HT),method="lm",color="darkgreen",se=FALSE,size=.5)+
    labs(title="Sapling Height vs. Diameter by Crown Class",
       subtitle="Wisconsin 2016-2019")

Looking at a violin plot

So- since my others were all so similar I thought I’d make the black spruce figure a violin plot to see what it looked like and if I could make sense of it. I’m very much against my use of colors here since if I were looking at it I would expect some meaning or legend associated with the colors- BUT- the plot looks pretty with the colors and rather boring without. I also don’t feel like this is especially useful for this particular variable because although we get a sense of the distribution of heights for each crown class, we don’t have the associated diameter data. I wouldn’t use this one but it gets me thinking…

ggplot()+
  geom_violin(data=trees2,mapping=aes(x=CCLCD,y=HT,color=CCLCD,fill=CCLCD),alpha=.3,trim=FALSE)+
  scale_x_discrete(name=NULL)+
  scale_y_continuous(name="Total Height (feet)")+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(panel.grid.major.x = element_blank())+
  theme(legend.position="none")+
    labs(title="Sapling Heights of Black Spruce by Crown Class",
       subtitle="Wisconsin 2016-2019")

Looking for potential changes over time in the relationship between diameter vs. height in a single species in WI.
